<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="95%"><TR bgcolor="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#00ff00" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">johnboy_0003</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Ok, I have a few newb questions that im sure many people are asking. Let me start with the basics. You have to have two computers networked togother, one has to be running linux, the other windows. The machine running linux will have showeq running on it.... got that, now my question is do you need to have 2 dial up accounts?</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Robotic</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">No.  <P><BR>Your Linux machine is connected to the internet.  Your Windoze machine runs EQ using the Linux machine's interent connection.  Thus your EQ info passes through the Linux machine which is running SEQ and sniffs (reads) the EQ info.<P>That is the layman's explanation.  If I'm wrong, someone here will correct me.   <IMG SRC="http://www.ethernalquest.com/ubb/smile.gif"><P><BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">shadowcat</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">You don't have to have your Linux box as the dialup.  As long as the computers are linked on a hub (rather than a switch), any computer can be the gateway.<P>I have my cable come into a router which has 2 Windows machines and my Linux on it.  I have that patched to an etherswitch which has my kid's PC and any other connections I want.  (Basically)<P>Now, if you want, you can use the Linux machine as your gateway and set up a firewall on it.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">batsmacker</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I have my SEQ box and EQ box Maqueraded behind a third linux box which my cable modem is connected to.<P>I have a question though: One of my fiends has a couple boxes networked together useing windows Internet Connection Sharing. Is there and way he can hook up a showEQ box to his network without buying or building some type or router?<P>I suppose he could set up the SEQ box as a router and IP MASQ but I dont wana talk him through all that over the phone =p<P>Thanks<BR>-Ryan<BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">XtremKaos</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Okay question here. I have a cable connection to the Inet. I send my cable modem to a 3com hub all 100baseT. I have 2 win9x machines connected to the hub and each has a seperate IP/username &lt;fucking @home and there usernames&gt; if I connect a linux box (thinking a laptop) to the 3com hub does the linux laptop have to be my gateway? or can it tap the info off the hub without the 2 win boxes playing EQ through it? or do I have to use the linux box as my gateway for one of the systems? I dual comp EQ and play 3 chars at once so kinda worried with lag due to pulling info through the linux laptop.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">FrozenInTime</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">You can tap the info from the linux machine without even having an IP address.  A similar technique is used for programs like the Snort NIDS.<P>Just config the device far enough that the kernel knows what driver to load for it and bring it up with:<P>ifconfig eth0 up<P>Then if you truly have a hub (and not a switch in disguise)  SEQ will be able to watch all the traffic flowing down the wire to it.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">johnboy_0003</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial"> thanks for the help)<P>I wanna be a zombie (have any hacks how? lol JK)</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">darkangelx</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">My network setup that works (not suggested)<BR>2 windoze boxes 1 slackware box all connected to a switch, DSL connected to uplink to switch, each box only has 1 nic, enter some wacked out info:<P>rc.inet1 had to be rigged<BR>{IPADDR}="192.0.0.1"<BR>{NETMASK="255.255.255.0"<BR>{GATEWAY}="192.0.0.2"<P>and then some code well i had to add new veriables under this but before the code making it look like this:<P>{IPADDR}="192.0.0.1"<BR>{NETMASK="255.255.255.0"<BR>{GATEWAY}="192.0.0.2"<P>{IPADDRA}="192.0.0.3"<BR>{NETMASKA}="255.255.255.0"<P>in doing this i assigned BOTH 192.0.0.1 and 192.0.03 to eth0 and bound them together.<P>then on the windoze boxes used<BR>ip 192.0.0.5<BR>sub 255.255.255.0<BR>gateway 192.0.0.3<BR>and<BR>ip 192.0.0.6<BR>sub 255.255.255.0<BR>gateway 192.0.0.3<P><BR>granted this works even with a switch (and no these IPS will NOT work so dont try it)</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">darkangelx</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">this is my rc.inet1 file located in /etc/rc.d/ directory for using 2 ips on 1 nic without masquarading but I have static ips and i will be changing the ips, also my static and ip block are on different subnets<P><BR># IF YOU HAVE AN ETHERNET CONNECTION, use these lines below to configure the<BR> eth0 interface.<P># Edit these values to set up a static IP address:<BR>IPADDR="192.0.0.1"        # REPLACE with YOUR IP address!<BR>NETMASK="255.255.255.102"       # REPLACE with YOUR netmask!<BR>NETWORK="192.0.0.128"       # REPLACE with YOUR network address!<BR>BROADCAST="192.0.0.255"     # REPLACE with YOUR broadcast address, if you<BR>                        # have one. If not, leave blank and edit below.<BR>GATEWAY="192.0.0.1"       # REPLACE with YOUR gateway address!<BR>****# test eth0:0<BR>IPADDRA="192.0.0.3"<BR>NETMASKA="255.255.255.100"****<P># To use DHCP instead of a static IP, set this value to "yes":<BR>DHCP="no"            # Use DHCP ("yes" or "no")<P># OK, time to set up the interface:<BR>if [ "$DHCP" = "yes" ]; then # use DHCP to set everything up:<BR>  echo "Attempting to configure eth0 by contacting a DHCP server..."<BR>  /sbin/dhcpcd<BR>elif [ ! "$IPADDR" = "127.0.0.1" ]; then # set up IP statically:<BR>  # Set up the ethernet card:<BR>  echo "Configuring eth0 as ${IPADDR}..."<BR>  /sbin/ifconfig eth0 ${IPADDR} broadcast ${BROADCAST} netmask ${NETMASK}<BR>****echo "Configuring eth0:0 as ${IPADDRA}..."<BR> /sbin/ifconfig eth0:0 ${IPADDRA} netmask ${NETMASKA}****<BR>  # If that didn't succeed, give the system administrator some hints:<BR>  if [ ! $? = 0 ]; then<BR>    cat &lt;&lt; EOF<P>(end file here)<P>ok if you see **** "info"**** that is something i had to ADD to this file to get it to route<P>then on the windows machines<BR>start settings control panel<BR>specify an ip<BR>IP 192.0.0.4 for 1 192.0.0.5 for other<BR>subnet mask 255.255.255.100 for both<BR>gate way tab 192.0.0.3<P>as you can see the gateway for the 2 windows boxes is the 2nd ip that is aliased to eth0:0 in /etc/rc.d/rc.inet1<P>please &lt;B&gt;NOTE&lt;/B&gt; this is for SLACKWARE not redhat or mandrake</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
</FONT>
